It is noteworthy that although the critical exponents so obtained are incorrect for many models and systems, they correctly satisfy various exponent equalities such as the Rushbrooke equality: formula_45.

===First-order transitions===
Landau theory can also be used to study first-order transitions. There are two different formulations, depending on whether or not the system is symmetric under a change in sign of the order parameter.

====I. Symmetric Case====
Here we consider the case where the system has a symmetry and the energy is invariant when the order parameter changes sign.
A first-order transition will arise if the quartic term in formula_46 is negative. To ensure that the free energy remains positive at large formula_1, one must carry the free-energy expansion to sixth-order,

:formula_48

where formula_49, and formula_50 is some temperature at which formula_51 changes sign. We denote this temperature by formula_50 and not formula_3, since it will emerge below that it is not the temperature of the first-order transition, and since there is no critical point, the notion of a &quot;critical temperature&quot; is misleading to begin with. formula_54 and formula_55 are positive coefficients.

We analyze this free energy functional as follows: (i) For formula_56, the formula_57 and formula_58 terms are concave upward for all formula_1, while the formula_60 term is concave downward. Thus for sufficiently high temperatures formula_46 is concave upward for all formula_1, and the equilibrium solution is formula_63. (ii) For formula_64, both the formula_57 and formula_60 terms are negative, so formula_63 is a local maximum, and the minimum of formula_46 is at some non-zero value formula_69, with
formula_70. (iii) For formula_71 just above formula_72, formula_63 turns into a local minimum, but the minimum at formula_74 continues to be the global minimum since it has a lower free energy. It follows that as the temperature is raised above formula_50, the global minimum cannot continuously evolve from
formula_74 to 0. Rather, at some intermediate temperature formula_77, the minima at formula_78 and formula_63 must become degenerate. For formula_80, the global minimum will jump discontinuously from formula_78 to 0.

