Once again formula_49, and formula_102 are all positive. The sign of the cubic term can always be chosen to be negative as we have done by reversing the sign of formula_1 if necessary.

We analyze this free energy functional as follows: (i) For formula_64, we have a local maximum at formula_63, and since the free energy is bounded below, there must be two local minima at nonzero values formula_106 and formula_107. The cubic term ensures that formula_108 is the global minimum since it is deeper. (ii) For formula_109 just above formula_50, the minimum at formula_111 disappears, the maximum at formula_63 turns into a local minimum, but the minimum at formula_108 persists and continues to be the global minimum. As the temperature is further raised, formula_114 rises until it equals zero at some temperature formula_77. At formula_77 we get a discontinuous jump in the global minimum from formula_117 to 0. (The minima cannot coalesce for that would require the first three derivatives of formula_46 to vanish at formula_63.)

To find formula_77, we demand that free energy be zero at formula_121 (just like the formula_84 solution), and furthermore that this point should be a local minimum. These two conditions yield two equations,
:formula_123
